3.1.2 Wrangle

df.exp1 = df.exp1 %>%
  filter(include == 1) %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = (bag: snail),
               names_to = "item",
               values_to = "rating",
               values_drop_na = TRUE) %>%
  relocate(participant_number, condition, item, rating, age, gender, lan_spoken) %>%
  mutate(kind = case_when(item == "bag" ~ 0,
                          item == "shoe" ~ 0,
                          item == "clock" ~ 0,
                          item == "phone" ~ 0,
                          item == "drum" ~ 0,
                          item == "spider" ~ 1,
                          item == "tree" ~ 1,
                          item == "snail" ~ 1)) %>%
  mutate(kind = factor(kind,
                       levels = c("0", "1"),
                       labels = c("artifact", "biological")))

# warm-up items
df.exp1.warmup = df.exp1 %>% 
  filter(item %in% c("bag", "shoe"))

#test items
df.exp1 = df.exp1 %>% 
  filter(!item %in% c("bag", "shoe"))

4.2.2 Frequentist analysis

###############################################################################
#In the paper, we report the results from the Bayesian analysis below 
#so as to be consistent with the reporting of studies 1 and 3 which also 
#used Bayesian analysis. 
#We preregistered that we would conduct a frequentist analysis for study 2,
#where we would use fit a generalized linear mixed effects model, 
#taking a model stacking approach for the random effect structure. 
#We preregistered that we would first fit a model with random intercepts for
#participants and then add an addition random intercept for trials, 
#comparing the models to see if the second improved model fit. 
#Then we would perform follow-up analyses with the best fitting model. 
#The results from this analysis and the 
#Bayesian analysis do not qualitatively differ.
###############################################################################

df.model = df.exp2 %>% 
  mutate(condition = as_factor(condition),
         condition= fct_relevel(condition, "purpose", "label_only", "irrelevant"))

# Fit the model with random intercepts for participants only
fit.glmer1 = glmer(rating ~ condition + (1 | participant),
                    data = df.model,
                    family = binomial,
                    control = glmerControl(optimizer = "bobyqa"))

# Fit the model with random intercepts for participants and items
fit.glmer2 = glmer(rating ~ condition + (1 | participant) + (1 | item),
                    data = df.model,
                    family = binomial,
                    control = glmerControl(optimizer = "bobyqa"))

# Compare the two models
anova(fit.glmer1, fit.glmer2)
